{"task_summary":"Balanced Brackets","approach":"I used a stack to keep track of opening and closing brackets. I started with an empty stack, then added each bracket to the stack as it was encountered. If the next bracket is not a matching pair (i.e., the top of my stack is not the same type of bracket that matches), then I return False immediately. Otherwise, if the top of my stack is the same type of bracket that matches, I pop from the stack and continue until there are no more brackets left to check.","code":"def balanced_brackets(string):
    openers = ['(', '{', '[']
    closers = [')', '}', ']']
    stack = []
    for char in string:
        if char not in openers and char not in closers:
            return False
        elif char in openers:
            stack.append(char)
        else:
            if len(stack) == 0 or stack[-1] != openers[closers.index(char)]:
                return False
            else:
                stack.pop()
    return True

print(balanced_brackets('([]{})'))
print(balanced_brackets('([)]'))","complexity":{"time":"O(N)","space":"O(N)"},"edge_cases":["None"],"tests":["assert balanced_brackets('([]{})') == True","assert balanced_brackets('([)]') == False","assert balanced_brackets('({[]})') == True","assert balanced_brackets('()[]{}') == True","assert balanced_brackets('(]{}') == False"],"risks":["None"]}

